-- 
Stocks in South Africa Rise for Fifth Day: Gold Fields, Eqstra, Trans Hex

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-05-30T16:15:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/stocks-in-south-africa-rise-for-a-fifth-day-led-by-gold-fields-anglogold.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rose for the fifth day, adding 5.5, or 0.02 percent, to
32,389.91 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Eqstra Holdings Ltd. (EQS)  , which imports industrial and
construction equipment, had its the strongest close since May
12, adding 20 cents, or 3.2 percent, to 6.50 rand after saying
earnings per share will be at least 60 cents for the year ended
June 30, compared with a loss per share of 19.6 cents a year
earlier.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , Africa’s second-largest producer
of the metal, gained 2.35 rand, or 2.1 percent, to 112.50 rand,
snapping two days of declines. Gold added 0.2 percent to
$1,539.40 an ounce in  London , having risen 1 percent to
$1,535.55 an ounce after the South African market closed on May
27, the highest since May 3.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. Ltd. (HAR SJ), the third-largest
producer, jumped to the highest since May 3, advancing 1.35
rand, or 1.4 percent, to 94.85 rand.  Illovo Sugar Ltd. (ILV)  ,  South Africa ’s biggest sugar
producer by market value, dropped 30 cents, or 1.2 percent, to
25.60 rand, snapping two days of increases. The company said it
expected a “marginal” increase in sugar production after
reporting net income fell 17 percent to 546 million rand ($79
million) in the year ended March 31.  Protech Khuthele Holdings Ltd. (PKH)  , a civil
engineering services provider, had its biggest one-day increase
since March 24, adding 5 cents, or 11 percent, to 50 cents. The
company said revenue rose 43 percent to 1.07 billion rand in the
year ended Feb. 28. It has contracts worth 1.4 billion rand
until 2013, the company said in a stock exchange statement.  Trans Hex Group Ltd. (TSX)   had its biggest gain since
May 10, rising 15 cents, or 5.7 percent, to 2.80 rand. The
diamond producer said its South African operations posted a
pretax profit of 116 million rand in the six months through
March 31 from a pretax loss of 101 million rand in the prior six
months.  UCS Group Ltd. (UCS)  , an information technology
provider, surged 5 cents, or 14 percent, to 41 cents, snapping
two days of decreases, after saying it may delist its shares
from the stock exchange.  To contact the reporter on this story:
